{{Cite need|date=January 2020}}
''''Rekichū''' (暦注) refers to annotations in a {{ill|calendar|ja|暦}} that indicate the auspiciousness (吉凶) of times, {{ill|directions|ja|方位}}, and other elements related to the fortune (運勢) of particular days.

== Overview ==

Most Rekichū are based on the principles of {{ill|Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|ja|陰陽五行説|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory}} and the {{ill|Heavenly Stems|lt=Ten Heavenly Stems|ja|十干}} and {{ill|Twelve Earthly Branches|ja|十二支}} ({{ill|Sexagenary cycle|ja|干支}}). Generally, calendars list scientific and astronomical details such as dates, {{ill|days of the week|ja|曜日}}, {{ill|solar terms|ja|二十四節気}}, and {{ill|72 pentads|ja|七十二候}} in the top section. The middle section typically features {{ill|Jūni choku|ja|十二直}}, while the lower section contains items like {{ill|Sembi|ja|選日|1=Senjitsu}}, {{ill|28 mansions|ja|二十八宿}}, {{ill|Nine Star Ki|ja|九星}}, and {{ill|Rekichū Gedan|ja|暦注下段}}. <!-- These middle and lower sections are collectively referred to as Rekichū. -->

{{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜}} often appears under the date and is also considered part of Rekichū.

The method used to determine the dates in Rekichū is called {{ill|Senpō|ja|撰日法}}.

