Most Rekichū are based on the principles of {{ill|Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|ja|陰陽五行説|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Heavenly Stems|lt=Ten Heavenly Stems|ja|十干|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Twelve Earthly Branches|ja|十二支|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Sexagenary cycle|ja|干支|12=draft|12=draft}}). Generally, calendars list scientific and astronomical details such as dates, {{ill|days of the week|ja|曜日|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|solar terms|ja|二十四節気|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|72 pentads|ja|七十二候|12=draft|12=draft}} in the top section. The middle section typically features {{ill|Jūni choku|ja|十二直|12=draft|12=draft}}, while the lower section contains items like {{ill|Sembi|ja|選日|1=Senjitsu|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|28 mansions|ja|二十八宿|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nine Star Ki|ja|九星|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rekichū Gedan|ja|暦注下段|12=draft|12=draft}}. <!-- These middle and lower sections are collectively referred to as Rekichū. -->
{{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|12=draft|12=draft}} often appears under the date and is also considered part of Rekichū.
The method used to determine the dates in Rekichū is called {{ill|Senpō|ja|撰日法|12=draft|12=draft}}.
